      Interest
   =20
 =20

You could imagine, I suppose, a =E2=80=9Cphysical dollar ETF=E2=80=9D that =
worked like this:
=09You send money to the ETF issuer.
  [1]

=09The issuer uses your money to buy crisp $100 bills.=09The issuer keeps t=
he $100 bills in a nice safe vault.=09The issuer charges fees to cover thin=
gs like its marketing cost, its cost of renting the vault, etc.

In some rough sense that=E2=80=99s how a physical gold ETF works, and it=E2=
=80=99s how a spot Bitcoin ETF works: There=E2=80=99s some stuff, the stuff=
 is a store of value, and the ETF keeps the stuff in a physical or cryptogr=
aphic vault, not doing anything with it.
But in fact there=E2=80=99d be something a bit crazy about doing that with =
dollars. There are  =E2=80=9Ccash=E2=80=9D ETFs, in some sense.
  [2]
=C2=A0But everyone understands that these ETFs don=E2=80=99t hold=C2=A0cris=
p $100 bills. They hold extremely safe interest-bearing short-term debt ins=
truments.
  [3]
=C2=A0If you invest your money in one of those ETFs, it will =E2=80=9Chold=
=E2=80=9D your =E2=80=9Ccash=E2=80=9D for you in roughly the sense that a b=
ank would
  [4]
: It will lend out your cash, as safely as possible, give it back to you on=
 demand, and=C2=A0pay you interest.=C2=A0
This is the natural way of the world, in finance. Even a=C2=A0stock=C2=A0ET=
F will probably do this: Stock ETFs often take their investors=E2=80=99 mon=
ey, use it to buy stocks, and then=C2=A0lend out some of those stocks to ea=
rn a bit of extra interest.
  [5]
=C2=A0Modern finance is=C2=A0very interested in efficiency, and abhors the =
idea of buying anything, putting it in a box, and=C2=A0doing nothing with i=
t. You=E2=80=99ve got some stuff in a box, you take it out of the box, you=
=C2=A0lend=C2=A0it to someone who wants to do something with it, and you ea=
rn interest.
The Satoshi Nakamoto vision of crypto was very different: This idea of buil=
ding opaque leverage into every part of the system, of constructing everyth=
ing on webs of debt, is part of what Bitcoin was reacting against.
But the modern vision of crypto, or at least the 2022 vision of crypto, was=
 like everything else in finance. You could hold Bitcoins in your digital w=
allet, like holding $100 bills in your regular wallet, but the action was i=
n depositing your Bitcoins with some quasi-bank that would lend them out, e=
arn interest, and pay some of the interest to you. This led to various terr=
ible problems, chiefly:
=09Those quasi-banks were   very highly leveraged, and when crypto prices f=
ell many of them collapsed and took their quasi-depositors=E2=80=99 money w=
ith them.=09The=C2=A0lending=C2=A0done by these platforms was pretty much a=
ll in support of speculative trading rather than real-world economic activi=
ty: People didn=E2=80=99t borrow Bitcoins to buy houses; they borrowed Bitc=
oins to make bets on Bitcoin prices. So the collapse was pretty sharp.=09Al=
so a fair amount of fraud.=09The US Securities and Exchange Commission is  =
 quite convinced, for fairly good=C2=A0reasons, that all of those crypto le=
nding platforms were=C2=A0securities, subject to securities regulation, and=
 that everyone running those platforms was doing so illegally.

Still, in the long run, if you have a giant pot full of electronic financia=
l assets, and if there is demand to borrow those assets, won=E2=80=99t you =
want to lend them? Ten=C2=A0years from now, if Bitcoin ETFs are still aroun=
d, is it more likely that they will be =E2=80=9Cphysical=E2=80=9D ETFs, jus=
t holding inert Bitcoins in a pot, or that they will be money-market-ish ET=
Fs, lending out their Bitcoins to earn=C2=A0interest and passing it along t=
o their investors?=C2=A0
Of course=C2=A0today=C2=A0the answer is =E2=80=9Cphysical=E2=80=9D; the pro=
spectuses for today=E2=80=99s Bitcoin ETFs say that they will hold the Bitc=
oins in custody, not that they will lend them. (Here is  Grayscale=E2=80=99=
s, and here=E2=80=99s  BlackRock=E2=80=99s.) And SEC Chair Gary Gensler=E2=
=80=99s statement on the Bitcoin ETF approvals says: =E2=80=9CImportantly, =
today=E2=80=99s Commission action is cabined to ETPs holding one non-securi=
ty commodity, bitcoin. It should in no way signal the Commission=E2=80=99s =
willingness to approve listing standards for crypto asset securities.=E2=80=
=9D Bitcoin lending is a security, in Gensler=E2=80=99s view, and not somet=
hing he wants to approve at this point.=C2=A0

