10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow and Monday, back on Tuesday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bitcoin ETF</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Taking a step back here, there is something re=
ally cool about=C2=A0what Bitcoin has accomplished, in some ways much coole=
r than <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33970375.25=
7410/aHR0cHM6Ly9iaXRjb2luLm9yZy9iaXRjb2luLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBea=
614a16" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> Satoshi Nakamoto=E2=80=99s original vision</a> for it. The=
 original vision of Bitcoin was that it would be =E2=80=9Celectronic cash,=
=E2=80=9D a way for people to send payments to each other without involving=
 a bank or other intermediary. Fifteen years later, I mean, there has been=
=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>progress along those lines;=C2=A0<em>some </em>peo=
ple sometimes do pay for some goods and services using Bitcoin. But it has =
not exactly taken over the world of payments. El Salvador made Bitcoin lega=
l tender and required all businesses to accept it, and even there it is <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33970375.257410/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cubmJlci5vcmcvZGlnZXN0LzIwMjIwNy9lbC1zYWx2YWRvcnMtZXhwZXJpbWVudC1i=
aXRjb2luLWxlZ2FsLXRlbmRlcg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2f805693" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> not =
that widely used</a>. In big developed economies, despite years of crypto p=
roselytizing, people still much prefer fiat currency and traditional banks.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And yet the price of Bitcoin has gone from zer=
o=C2=A0in 2009 to $46,000-ish today, not on widespread adoption as a=C2=A0<=
em>payments=C2=A0</em>mechanism, but because people =E2=80=94=C2=A0lots of =
people, crypto evangelists but also regular retail investors and quite trad=
itional investment strategists at big institutional investment firms =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0view it as a =E2=80=9Cstore of value.=E2=80=9D Which means that th=
ey think its price will go up, or at least not go down, robustly and for th=
e long term. They buy Bitcoin at $46,000 not because they plan to use it as=
 digital cash, but because they think other people will buy it at $47,000, =
or $470,000 or whatever.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which is why people buy Apple Inc. stock, or T=
reasury bonds or oil futures or whatever: They think other people will buy =
them, so the price will go up. You know <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/33970375.257410/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa=
2kvS2V5bmVzaWFuX2JlYXV0eV9jb250ZXN0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6d1491b1" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;"> what Keynes said</a>.=C2=A0But those things have cash flows or industr=
ial uses; those things are claims on economic activity. Bitcoin is just a t=
hing a guy made up 15 years ago. Its function as a store of value is almost=
 purely self-referential: Not =E2=80=9Cthis is worth $X because other peopl=
e will buy it for $X because other people will buy it for $X because =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0[etc.] =E2=80=A6 other people think its cash flows have a present =
value of $X,=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Cthis is worth $X because other people wi=
ll buy it for $X because other people will buy it for $X=E2=80=9D all the w=
ay down.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bitcoin is an astonishing=C2=A0<em>social tech=
nology.</em>=C2=A0It would, in the abstract, be useful for the world if the=
re was just an entry in a computer database that we all agreed was valuable=
 <em>just because</em>, with no reference to any underlying commodity or se=
ries of cash flows or industrial activity. Just a number that was valuable.=
 And so someone invented it. Traditionally <em>currency=C2=A0</em>works sor=
t of like that: The US dollar is this sort of social technology; it has val=
ue because it has value, not because it has cash flows. But there=E2=80=99s=
 a whole ton of complex and long-standing social technology that goes into =
that; the US has a government and=C2=A0an army and an income tax and a debt=
 stock and a trade balance, which help to preserve the value of the dollar.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bitcoin expresses the thesis that it would be =
good to have a valuable database entry=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>that, jus=
t something was valuable because people on the internet voluntarily agreed =
it was valuable, with no government or army or taxes or anything else. And =
it worked! That did happen. It has value due to a broad voluntary market co=
nsensus based almost entirely on itself. In some sense that consensus is fr=
agile =E2=80=94=C2=A0if a thing is valuable only because people think that =
it is valuable, it could stop being valuable when they stop thinking that =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but in another sense that is true of any social fact: The do=
llar is valuable, the King of England is the King of England, the US is a l=
iberal democracy, etc., exactly as long as those facts command social conse=
nsus. Bitcoin got to what seems like a pretty robust consensus in 15 years.=
 That=E2=80=99s=C2=A0just neat.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/33970375.257410/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMTAvc3BvdC1iaXRjb2luLWV0ZnMtYXBwcm92ZWQtdG8tbG=
F1bmNoLWluLXVzLWJ5LWdlbnNsZXItcy1zZWM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExMTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmd=
XRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTExJnV0=
bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6fec3870" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">as =
expected</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US regulators for the first time approved exch=
ange-traded funds that invest directly in Bitcoin, a move heralded as a lan=
dmark event for the roughly $1.7 trillion digital-asset sector that will br=
oaden access to the largest cryptocurrency on Wall Street and beyond.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission, whose =
three-part mandate includes investor protection, authorized funds from indu=
stry heavyweights BlackRock, Invesco and Fidelity to smaller competitors in=
cluding Valkyrie to begin trading Thursday.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The approvals mark a rare capitulation by the =
SEC following opposition that lasted for more than a decade, ever since Tyl=
er and Cameron Winklevoss first proposed a Bitcoin ETF in 2013. BlackRock I=
nc.=E2=80=99s surprise application last June, followed by an appeals court =
ruling that called the denial of a different application =E2=80=9Carbitrary=
 and capricious,=E2=80=9D triggered a blistering rally in the cryptocurrenc=
y amid speculation that US regulators would finally give their blessing to =
the structure.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is something pure about this, as Bitcoin=
 news. A Bitcoin ETF is vastly=C2=A0<em>less=C2=A0</em>useful, as a payment=
s mechanism or a way to supplant the traditional financial system, than jus=
t buying Bitcoin: Instead of an alternative peer-to-peer payments system in=
 which everyone can hold their Bitcoins directly and transfer them to each =
other without middlemen, this is a crypto thing that you can hold in your t=
raditional brokerage account and not use for payments at all. But it is <em=
>more</em> useful as a store of value: You can hold it in your brokerage ac=
count, where you hold your stores of value. You don=E2=80=99t have to mess =
around with an alternative financial system; you can just isolate the store=
-of-value component of Bitcoin and hold it directly. And so the price of Bi=
tcoin ran up in anticipation of the ETF approvals, because everyone expecte=
d that the ETFs would lead to more people holding Bitcoin as a store of val=
ue. Which is the best reason for Bitcoin to go up.</p>
