than $46,000, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3397=
0375.257410/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDE=
tMTEvYml0Y29pbi1idGMtdm9sdW1lLWp1bXBzLWFzLWZpcnN0LXVzLXNwb3QtZXRmcy1iZWdpbi=
10cmFkaW5nP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTEyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX=
3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDExMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVm=
Zg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfa417ccd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  before falling back</a>:</p=
>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bitcoin pared gains after surging past $49,000=
 for the first time since December 2021 with trading commencing for the fir=
st US exchange-traded funds that invest directly in the biggest cryptocurre=
ncy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The token had advanced as much as 6.7% to $49,=
021, buoyed by the approval of spot Bitcoin ETFs by the US Securities and E=
xchange Commission after markets closed on Wednesday. It was recently tradi=
ng at around $46,000. Most smaller tokens, such as Ether, Cardano and Polka=
dot were higher.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of the 11 ETFs are trading, and over $2.6 =
billion has changed hands in just the first few hours of trading.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The market reaction to the SEC=E2=80=99s fake =
approval of Bitcoin ETFs =E2=80=94=C2=A0a quick modest spike followed by a =
disappointed modest fall =E2=80=94=C2=A0is remarkably similar to the market=
 reaction to the SEC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>real=C2=A0</em>approval of Bitcoin =
ETFs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, I wrote yesterday that, while it is poss=
ible that someone hacked the SEC=E2=80=99s Twitter to make money by manipul=
ating the price of Bitcoin, it was also possible that whoever did the hack =
was just trolling for fun, and did=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>make any money by=
 manipulating Bitcoin. Several readers emailed to point out the strongest a=
rgument for that possibility: If you wanted to manipulate the market, you w=
ould=C2=A0<em>short </em>Bitcoin and then hack the SEC to tweet =E2=80=9Cwe=
=E2=80=99re once again <em>declining</em> to approve Bitcoin ETFs, too many=
 problems, we=E2=80=99re confident we=E2=80=99ll win in court this time.=E2=
=80=9D The market really expected the SEC to approve the ETFs, so there was=
 not a ton of information in Tuesday=E2=80=99s fake tweet, and it didn=E2=
=80=99t move the price of Bitcoin that much. But if the fake tweet had=C2=
=A0<em>confounded=C2=A0</em>expectations,=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>would hav=
e moved the market. If you were a ruthless hacker/manipulator looking to ma=
ximize profits, that=E2=80=99s what you=E2=80=99d do. If you were a crypto =
enthusiast looking to troll the SEC for fun, though, you=E2=80=99d fake-twe=
et that the ETFs were approved.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, by the way, the SEC=E2=80=99s approval i=
s hilariously grudging. Here=E2=80=99s SEC Chair <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33970375.257410/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9u=
ZXdzL3N0YXRlbWVudC9nZW5zbGVyLXN0YXRlbWVudC1zcG90LWJpdGNvaW4tMDExMDIz/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB1034a85d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Gary Gensler=E2=80=99s statement</a>:=
</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Though we=E2=80=99re merit neutral, I=E2=80=99=
d note that ... bitcoin is primarily a speculative, volatile asset that=E2=
=80=99s also used for illicit activity including ransomware,=C2=A0money lau=
ndering, sanction evasion, and terrorist financing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While we approved the listing and trading of c=
ertain spot bitcoin ETP shares today, we did not approve or endorse bitcoin=
. Investors should remain cautious about the myriad risks associated with b=
itcoin and products whose value is tied to crypto.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And here is Commissioner <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33970375.257410/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmd=
vdi9uZXdzL3N0YXRlbWVudC9jcmVuc2hhdy1zdGF0ZW1lbnQtc3BvdC1iaXRjb2luLTAxMTAyMw=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9eea7c22" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Caroline Crenshaw=E2=80=99s di=
ssent from the approval</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Spot bitcoin markets are subject to fraud and =
manipulation. One form of manipulation that appears to be pervasive in the =
crypto markets (and specifically bitcoin markets), is wash trading, a pract=
ice whereby traders seek to increase the appearance of high trading interes=
t by both selling and buying the same products at the same time, often driv=
ing up prices, and then selling to unwitting third party market participant=
s at inflated values. Wash trading distorts price and volume, causes volati=
lity, reduces investor confidence and participation in financial markets, a=
nd of course, results in investor harm. One analysis of 29 major crypto exc=
hanges found that wash trading was, on average, as high as 77.5% of the tot=
al trading volume on unregulated exchanges. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Specifically with regard to bitcoin, an analys=
is of 157 crypto exchanges found that 51% of the reported daily bitcoin tra=
ding volume was likely bogus. In fact, though reporting regarding bitcoin f=
requently discusses the enormous size of the market, one market participant=
 who now seeks to sponsor a spot bitcoin ETP has admitted that =E2=80=9Capp=
roximately 95%=E2=80=9D of the data used by many participants are =E2=80=9C=
fake and/or non-economic.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6 In short, prices and demand fo=
r bitcoin may not actually be what they appear to be.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I joked yesterday that the SEC should deny all=
 of these applications, saying =E2=80=9CWe<em> were</em> going to approve t=
hem, but it turns out that the Bitcoin market is still too vulnerable to ma=
nipulation, as you can tell by the fact that someone hacked our Twitter to =
manipulate Bitcoin.=E2=80=9D Crenshaw makes that argument!</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Indeed, just yesterday, prior to t=
he issuance of our approval Order, one of the SEC=E2=80=99s social media ac=
counts was compromised, and an unauthorized post falsely indicated that we =
had approved spot bitcoin ETFs.=C2=A0Unsurprisingly, the price of spot bitc=
oin suffered =E2=80=9Cwhiplash=E2=80=9D in the minutes and hours following =
the false tweet.=C2=A0While the facts underlying this misconduct hopefully =
will be uncovered by law enforcement in the future, I will be monitoring wh=
at may be yet another attempt to profit from wrongdoing in this market.</p>=
</blockquote>
