<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One other what-will-the-future-bring sort of p=
oint about Bitcoin ETFs. The normal way that, say, a stock index ETF works =
is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Normal people buy and sell shares of =
the ETF on the exchange: They don=E2=80=99t actually give any money to the =
ETF issuer; they just trade in the secondary market.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">Arbitrageurs make sure that the price of the ETF and the=
 price of the index stay in line: If the price of ETF shares gets too high,=
 arbs will sell ETF shares and buy the underlying index.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">To complete the arbitrage, a few big banks or trad=
ing firms, called =E2=80=9Cauthorized participants,=E2=80=9D can=C2=A0<em>e=
xchange=C2=A0</em>the ETF shares for the underlying index: They can collect=
 a basket of all the stocks in the index, deliver them to the ETF issuer, a=
nd get back some new ETF shares (this is called =E2=80=9Ccreation), or they=
 can collect some ETF shares, deliver them to the ETF issuer for retirement=
, and get back a basket of the underlying stocks (this is called =E2=80=9Cr=
edemption=E2=80=9D).</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">ETFs work this way in part for price efficienc=
y reasons (in-kind creation and redemption makes it=C2=A0easier to arbitrag=
e the ETF against its underlying index), in part for operational efficiency=
 reasons (it means the ETF doesn=E2=80=99t have to do much trading for itse=
lf),=C2=A0and in=C2=A0large part for tax efficiency reasons (it means=C2=A0=
that the ETF <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33970=
375.257410/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTkt=
